@node UPGRADE "How/When to UPGRADE this work..."
===========================================================================
           Cnet Amiga Who, v2.73 by Dotoran of Frontiers BBS!
===========================================================================
    If you're using this mod for the first time, please refer to the section
titled @{"How to Install It" link INSTALL} for instructions on installing and using this mod
on your bbs.

If using v2.71 or v2.72:
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
    If you're presently using v2.71 or v2.72, then all you'll need to do 
is replace all major command files with the newer ones stored in this 
archive. This includes the: Short, Normal, and Long modules, as well as 
the Config and MakeWho modules. The README and HISTORY files have also 
been updated and the other files, like the Loader simply had their version 
number updated.

    You do NOT have to replace any of the DATA and/or CONFIG files, as there
were NO changes made to these files.

If using v2.00 thru v2.65:
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
    If you're using v2.00 thru v2.65, and want to UPGRADE to v2.73, follow 
these steps:

    Copy the CONFIG, LOADER, MAKEWHO, SHORT, NORMAL, and LONG command files
OVER the existing ones in your system. These command files had changes made
to them which allows them to run on v4.54+ (or v3.05c) CNet, but note that 
these files will NOT, repeat NOT run on a version of CNet Amiga versions
between v4.00 and 4.53, as these versions use getuser values NOT supported
by this version.

    You MUST be using v2.66 or newer in order to upgrade to this version. If 
using a version OLDER than 2.65, please grab a copy of 2.65 and upgrade to 
that one FIRST, then upgrade to this one, else install this one from scratch.

    You will need to run the included "Upgrade271" script from within Cnet to
convert your "Config.data" file over to the CTRL-S format I am now using, as
I'll no longer be coding using the CTRL-A's. It's an ARexx file, so you can
either add it as such, or else use one of the RUNA commands.

    Do NOT copy the CONFIG.DATA, IDLEPORTS, _BANNERS, _GLIMPSE, or _HISTORY
files, unless you wish to overwrite any custom settings you may have made
to one or more of these in the past.

    Lastly, replace the WHO_README and WHO_HISTORY files with the updated
versions found in this archive.

    That's It! Enjoy!
                                                                  - Dotoran
@endnode
@node SUPERUSER "How to enable/disable the `SuperUser' privilege flag..."
How to Enable/Disable the `SuperUser' Privilege Flag
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
   When the `SuperUser' flag was first introduced in CNet, v4.xx, it was
automatically ENABLED in every user's account.

   When fully implemented, this new flag will carry a similar function as
that of the `System Operator' flag, except that this flag will determine
if a user will have `root access' powers to the Internet applets which are
coming to CNet Amiga in the very near future. Things like being able to
finger ANYONE, being able to work with ANY file in ANY directory using the
FTP commands, being automatically given "op" status in the IRC client, etc.

   So, knowing this, chances are this is NOT a flag you'll want to give to
ALL of your users. Here's how you can DISABLE the new `SuperUser' flag in
the user accounts on YOUR bbs's, using CNet's own EA VDE Editor:

1. Logon to your bbs, then type the following from the main command prompt:

        EA 1-       (So that you can edit ALL accounts)

2. You'll then be asked which access groups you wish the changes to be made
   to. Enter the range of groups you wish to DISABLE the flag in, perhaps:

        0-30        (So only Group 31's would HAVE the flag enabled)

3. You'll then be presented with the EA VDE screen, but will note that ALL
   the entries are ghosted(in black). Move to the second column and select
   the "Privilege flags    >>" option.

4. Once on the "Privileges" screen, go to the LAST item in the third column,
   "SuperUser      :", then press your ENTER key until you see the word "No"
   appear.

5. Move to the "Exit" option, press ENTER, then press ENTER while the "Save
   changes" option is highlighted.

6. That's It! Now just sit back and let CNet do the rest!

   How LONG the operation will take will depend on the number of accounts
you have, as well as your CPU type. (On my A=2000, with over 400 accounts,
it took close to a minute to complete the operation).

   Once complete, you'll notice an "S" following the Port Number in the WHO
displays(both MINE and in CNet's internal version). This "S" flag Supersedes
all other displays that could appear here.
@endnode
